EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong to severe thunderstorms moved across parts of east central Illinois during the afternoon hours of May 17th producing mainly hail and one brief tornado.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A small and brief tornado reportedly touched down in a field about five miles west of Paxton.  No damage was reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong to severe thunderstorms moved across parts of northwest Indiana during the afternoon hours of May 7th producing mainly hail.
Strong to severe thunderstorms moved across parts of northwest Indiana during the afternoon hours of May 7th producing mainly hail.
Strong to severe thunderstorms moved across parts northern Illinois during the afternoon hours of May 12th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail was reported near Nelson and Hartland Roads.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong to severe thunderstorms moved across parts northern Illinois during the afternoon hours of May 12th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Small tree limbs and a traffic sign were blown down.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong to severe thunderstorms moved across parts northern Illinois during the afternoon hours of May 12th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two 10 inch diameter trees were blown down blocking Broadway Road, about one half mile east of Keystone Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong to severe thunderstorms moved across many areas of northwest Indiana during the evening hours of May 11th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail was reported near Robin Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong to severe thunderstorms moved across many areas of northwest Indiana during the evening hours of May 11th.

Strong to severe thunderstorms developed over parts of northern Illinois during the afternoon hours of May 13th.  These storms produced very heavy rain and were slow moving, which led to flooding in some areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Cherry Valley Road was flooded with 6 to 12 inches of standing water.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Widely scattered thunderstorms developed along a stationary frontal boundary during the afternoon of June 15th.  One of the cells began to rotate and eventually produced two weak tornadoes across Shelby County.  Other storms dropped penny-sized hail near Robinson in Crawford County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tornado briefly touched down in a field about 6 miles east of Windsor.  No damage occurred.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of low pressure tracking from northern Missouri into the southern Great Lakes triggered scattered thunderstorms across central Illinois during the afternoon and evening of June 10th into the early morning hours of the 11th.  A few of the storms produced large hail up to the size of golf balls, as well as gusty winds of 50 to 60 mph.  In addition, a brief tornado touch down occurred in rural Schuyler County near Littleton.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms with intense rainfall produced 3.00 to 4.00 inches of rain in one hour during the late afternoon in northwest Clay County. Creeks rapidly spread out of their banks and numerous rural roads were flooded.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An early morning complex of thunderstorms developed north of a warm front in southeast Iowa and northeast Missouri. These thunderstorms moved into a small part of west central Illinois, resulting in heavy rain and flash flooding in Scott County during the morning hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rainfall amounts of 3.50 to 5.00, most of which fell between 0500 and 0700 LST, resulted in significant flash flooding across western Scott County. Sandy Creek was out of it's banks, and numerous rural roads were impassable.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Outflow from a thunderstorm collided with a sea breeze boundary and allowed a severe thunderstorm to develop.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees were knocked down along U.S. Highway 11 in McNeil.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An outflow boundary collided with a lake breeze boundary to develop a strong thunderstorm over Lake Pontchartrain.
An outflow boundary collided with a lake breeze boundary to develop a strong thunderstorm over Lake Pontchartrain.
An upper air disturbance combined with very unstable air to develop an isolated severe thunderstorm during the afternoon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were blown down near the intersection of U.S. Highway 61 and Louisiana Highway 54. One tree fell on a business.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak impulse aloft moved across the area during the late afternoon and evening and sparked isolated thunderstorms. One storm across Robeson County split and moved south along a north-south seabreeze boundary producing large hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail to the size of quarters was reported at the intersection of Harris Road and Highway 211.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A broken line of thunderstorms developed along the lee side of the Appalachians during the middle of the afternoon. These thunderstorms then moved into Robeson and Bladen counties during the evening. Wind damage was associated with the gust front which preceded the actual thunderstorms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple trees were reported down along Old Red Springs Road. The time was estimated based on radar data.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorm complexes moved southeast from Kentucky into Tennessee. Outflow boundaries from these complexes moved eastward into Virginia and touched of showers and storms. Some of these storms increased to severe levels and produced damaging thunderstorm winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorm winds blew a few small trees down near Highland Ave SE. Damage values are estimated.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorm winds brought down a tree onto a power pole and power line at 700 Orange Ave. NE. Damage values are estimated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: With intense insolation and a weak surface trough across the forecast area, as well as an increasingly moist and unstable air mass, scattered severe storms developed across the region. Aided by an approaching mid level disturbance, these storms were able to persist through the evening hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown down several miles southwest of Moncure.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter reported an estimated wind gust of 62 mph just southwest of Raleigh. Numerous trees were blown down along a swath from just southwest of Raleigh to just northeast of Raleigh. There was also a report of quarter size hail in northeast Raleigh.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A Squall Line developed along the Interstate 135 corridor around 3 pm on the 20th and moved east through the evening into Southeast Kansas.   The storms were pretty potent as they produced widespread hail and damaging winds across the eastern one half of the state.

A strong area of low pressure moved from the Southern Plains into the Middle Mississippi Valley from April 19th into April 20th. A trailing cold front moved into the Mid-South during the nighttime hours of April 19th resulting in numerous severe storms with large hail and damaging wind. This front slowly moved across the region eventually stalling across North Mississippi on April 20th resulting in more severe storms and isolated flash flooding.
